Autoimmune enteropathy is suggested by the longstanding history of villous blunting despite a GFD and 
the concurrent history of an immune-mediated disorder, rheumatoid arthritis. While typically more common 
in males, several genetic conditions have been associated with the diagnosis of autoimmune enteropathy to 
include IPEX (Immunodysregulation Polyendocrinopathy Enteropathy X-linked Syndrome) and APECED 
(Autoimmune Phenomena, Polyendocrinopathy, Candidiasis, and Ectodermal Dystrophy). In this case, 
subsequent genetic testing revealed a pathogenic sequence change in the CTLA4 gene consistent with a 
diagnosis of CTLA-4 haploinsufficiency
